title: Replies to initial written questions raised by Finance Committee Members in examining the Estimates of Expenditure 2012-13
question_text: (a) Currently, how many government buildings have obtained internationally recognised green building certification? Please give a detailed breakdown by category and level of certification. (b) Does the government plan to apply for internationally recognised green building certification for all government buildings? If yes, please provide relevant details such as the working schedule. (c) How much resource does the government intend to invest on incorporating green building features in government buildings? Please provide relevant details and a specific working schedule.
reply_text: (a) Starting from 1999, the Architectural Services Department (ArchSD) has participated in the Hong Kong Building Environmental Assessment Method (HKBEAM), a recognized building environmental performance assessment system currently administered by the Hong Kong Green Building Council. The list of assessed projects which have obtained the second highest rating or above under the BEAM assessment is at Annex. (b) In line with guidelines provided by the Development Bureau, all new government buildings with construction floor area of more than 10 000 m2 are required to be assessed by HKBEAM. For existing buildings, the scope for improvement on green building features would be through retrofitting and renovation as and when appropriate. (c) In 2012-13, ArchSD plans to carry out 71 improvement projects and the estimated expenditure for 2012-13 is $69 million on installation of green roofs or green building features to existing government buildings. Signature: Name in block letters: K K LEUNG Post Title: Director of Architectural Services Date: 28.2.2012 Session 15 FSTB(Tsy) – page Annex Government Buildings which have obtained the Second Highest Rating or above under BEAM Assessment Note Session 15 FSTB(Tsy) – page Annex (Cont’d) - 2 - Note : BEAM assessment method has been evolving over the years with different versions. For projects with applications for assessment submitted before 2003, the highest and the second highest ratings were “Excellent” and “Very Good” respectively. For projects submitted for assessment from 2003 onwards, the highest and the second highest ratings are “Platinum” and “Gold” respectively. Session 15 FSTB(Tsy) – page
